===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|seem}}, {{m|enm|seme}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|sēam||seam}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*saumaz||that which is sewn}}. Cognate with West Frisian {{term|seam|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|zoom|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Saum|lang=de}}, Swedish {{term|söm|lang=sv}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|sewing|lang=en}} A [[folded]] back and [[stitch]]ed piece of [[fabric]]; especially, the stitching that joins two or more pieces of fabric.<sup>{{w|Seam (sewing)|Wp}}</sup>
#* {{RQ:Chrsty Atbgrfy|II|4}}
#*: Mind you, clothes were clothes in those days. [&hellip;]&nbsp; Frills, ruffles, flounces, lace, complicated '''seams''' and gores: not only did they sweep the ground and have to be held up in one hand elegantly as you walked along, but they had little capes or coats or feather boas.
# A [[suture]].
# A thin [[stratum]], especially of [[coal]] or [[mineral]].
# {{context|cricket|lang=en}} The stitched [[equatorial]] seam of a [[cricket ball]]; the [[sideways]] [[movement]] of a ball when it [[bounce]]s on the seam.
# An old English [[measure]] of [[grain]], containing eight [[bushel]]s.
# An old English measure of [[glass]], containing twenty-four [[wey]]s of five [[pound]]s, or 120 pounds.
#* '''1952''', [[w:en:Louis Francis Salzman|L. F. Salzman]], ''Building in England'', p. 175.
#*: As white glass was 6s. the 'seam', containing 24 'weys' (pise, or pondera) of 5 lb., and 2&frac12; lb. was reckoned sufficient to make one foot of glazing, the cost of glass would be 1&frac12;d. leaving 2&frac12;d. for labour.
# {{context|construction|lang=en}} A joint formed by mating two separate sections of materials.
#: '''''Seams''' can be made or sealed in a variety of ways, including adhesive bonding, hot-air welding, solvent welding, using adhesive tapes, sealant, etc.''
# A line or depression left by a cut or wound; a [[scar]]; a [[cicatrix]].
# {{context|figurative|lang=en}} A line of junction; a joint.
#* {{w|Joseph Addison}} (1672-1719)
#*: Precepts should be so finely wrought together{{...}}that no coarse '''seam''' may discover where they join.

